{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"f6923e1c-3014-4de4-9d12-8b8acba49c3a","content":"## What happened\n\n.NET 11 marks `DSA` as `[UnsupportedOSPlatform(\"osx\")]`. Calling `DSA.Create()` on macOS now throws **`PlatformNotSupportedException`**.\n\nThis is part of Microsoft's progressive removal of legacy crypto algorithms. Apple's Security framework has never natively supported DSA, and .NET dropped its software fallback on macOS in .NET 11.\n\n## How to fix it\n\nSince you only need to **verify** legacy signatures (not create new ones), use **BouncyCastle**, which provides a managed DSA implementation that works on all platforms:\n\n```bash\ndotnet add package BouncyCastle.Cryptography\n```\n\nThen replace the platform-dependent code:\n\n```csharp\n// Before (.NET 10) — breaks on macOS in .NET 11\nusing var dsa = DSA.Create();\ndsa.ImportSubjectPublicKeyInfo(publicKeyBytes, out _);\nbool valid = dsa.VerifyData(data, signature, HashAlgorithmName.SHA1);\n```\n\n```csharp\n// After — works everywhere via BouncyCastle\nusing Org.BouncyCastle.Crypto.Parameters;\nusing Org.BouncyCastle.Security;\n\nvar publicKey = PublicKeyFactory.CreateKey(publicKeyBytes);\nvar verifier = SignerUtilities.GetSigner(\"SHA1withDSA\");\nverifier.Init(forSigning: false, publicKey);\nverifier.BlockUpdate(data, 0, data.Length);\nbool valid = verifier.VerifySignature(signature);\n```\n\n**Longer term:** plan to migrate away from DSA entirely—it's a legacy algorithm. ECDSA or Ed25519 are modern replacements.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"98ce1063-8f1f-429f-83ab-6abbb9a65420","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a .NET compatibility issue with DSA (Digital Signature Algorithm) on macOS after upgrading from .NET 10 to .NET 11. Let me think about what I know about this topic.\n\nThis is a well-known breaking change in .NET. Starting with .NET 7, Microsoft began deprecating older cryptographic algorithms, and DSA specifically has been affected on macOS.\n\nHere's what happened:\n\nIn .NET 7+, Apple's Security framework (which .NET uses on macOS) dropped support for DSA. The `DSA.Create()` method throws a `PlatformNotSupportedException` on macOS because the underlying platform (Apple's CommonCrypto/Security framework) no longer supports DSA.\n\n\nThe timeline is a bit fuzzy here—DSA support was progressively marked as unsupported across different platforms starting in .NET 7, with macOS being affected in later versions. Given that .NET 10 came out around November 2025 and .NET 11 is in preview now in May 2026, the user is likely hitting a breaking change that became more strict or visible in the newer version.\n\nThe core issue is that DSA on macOS relies on Apple's Security framework, and when Apple deprecated DSA support in their cryptographic APIs, .NET lost the ability to provide it. Microsoft has been removing support for older crypto algorithms across recent .NET versions, so this is probably part of that broader deprecation effort.\n\nFor someone hitting this in a .NET 11 migration, the practical solution would be to switch to a library like BouncyCastle that implements DSA independently, rather than relying on the OS-level cryptographic APIs. That works if they need to verify legacy DSA signatures, though ideally they'd migrate away from DSA entirely.","outputTokens":1249,"requestId":"401F:1E7C59:159D8F4:1871432:69F94ACF"},"id":"3bb79422-d6b9-4768-9fe5-d65e449a998f","timestamp":"2026-05-05T01:42:00.692Z","parentId":"90df0625-cc8b-444c-8218-07ec2c4fac51"}
